  "prompt": "A mexican politician said that if Donald trump would try to renegotiate NAFTA Mexico would try to renegotiate the treaty of Hidalgo. Is it possible?",
  "response": "The Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo (not Hidalgo) was signed in 1848 at the end of the Mexican-American War. This treaty resulted in Mexico ceding approximately half of its territory to the United States, including what are now the states of California, Nevada, Utah, most of Arizona, and parts of New Mexico, Colorado, and Wyoming.\n\nFrom a legal and practical standpoint, it is not possible to \"renegotiate\" this treaty in the way the politician suggested. The treaty is a historical document that has long been implemented, and the territorial changes are permanent. The statement was likely a rhetorical device meant to express Mexico's displeasure with potential NAFTA renegotiations, using historical context to emphasize Mexico's position.\n\nThe comment was more of a political statement meant to demonstrate Mexico's resolve during NAFTA negotiations, rather than a serious proposal to revisit the 19th-century territorial settlement.",
